item.title: Homework 1.H
item.dc:creator: tprebel
item.content:encoded: Please use this space to discuss Homework 1.H.

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: Where do SA and SB start from its kind of confusing depending on how you look at it, so I am just going to have O as my relative point
I think having O as your relative point is ok since the radii of the pulley are small. But I think they mean the dotted line as the starting point for SA and SB.
Set your function of L in terms of SA and SB. Then differentiate the whole function and you will get 0 = function of SA,SB,VA and VB. From there, you can plug in the given data to find VB.

For this problem solve for Sc (the length from A to O) in terms of Sa use Pythagorean theorem. do not plug in Sa= 0 or 4 just yet leave everything in variable form then plug in all the components for L and take the derivative of L (you are going to need to use the chain rule). form there solve in terms of Vb because dSb/dt = Vb and then you can plug in chug. you can also use this equation for part B.
But we don't know SB. How did you solve for SB in order to calculate VB?
We never need to explicitly find a length for SB. What is important is that we can relate the rate of change over time of SB to the speed of B and to the rate of change over time of SA.

You can use the law of cosines to find the angle OBA. Then I used the law of sines to find the i component of the position vectors. Then the pythagorean theorem to find the j component of the OA position vector.

You can use the law of cosines to find the angle BOA, but also, you don't need to use the law of sines or the pythagorean theorem to find the components. Make an imaginary right triangle above OA, and do 180 degrees minus angle BOA, to get angle right above OA. Now all you need to do is simple trigonometry to get your components!

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: Can we assume v rel is constant? If not, how did you decide the value for relative acceleration?

You would then use newton's equations in the x and y direction along with the fact that the normal force is equal to mu times the friction force. This gives you four equations and four unknowns which you should then be able to solve for

Does B really ever contact the bumper? The entire system of A and B together could be said to contact the bumper, because A contacts the bumper, but the line of impact between A and B is parallel to the bumper. A strikes the bumper an B simultaneously, but B is only propelled in the X direction; if you take the system of B alone, momentum is conserved along the Y direction (Normal to the line of impact). B can never gain any velocity towards the bumper, and can thus never contact the bumper.
And there is no need to solve for any initial velocities; they're both given to you, albeit in magnitude-angle form.
B will never contact the bumper. If you calculate the impact and restitution, you can calculate B to be going into the right parallel to the bumper.

If you consider your system to be only the bar, then there is a POTENTIAL reaction force from the roller along the x axis. But that reaction force is an unknown, and just adds complexity to the system. We can allow our system to include the roller at no cost; since the roller is massless, it doesn't affect the moment of inertia. When you do that, the only forces are the force of weight on the bar and the vertical reaction force between the roller and the guide. There's nothing wrong with Ax being 0, it just means that the center of mass can only bob up and down.
<3
Your response seems to be OK, but based on scheme / figure how can we say center of mass can only bob up and down? I am not too sure.

I had a big blob of text written up, but this video is much more convincing.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uOUXsMP-ORI

Big blob of text:
1) Take a standard coordinate system: X+ is right, Y+ is up. 2) Take your system to be the combination of the smooth, massless roller and the thin bar. Because the roller is massless, the COM of our system is the same as the COM of the bar on its own. 3) Consider the forces applied on our system. The bar has mass, so it is subjected to its own weight, a purely Y force. This is applied at the COM
There is a reactive force between the horizontal guide and the roller. Is there an X component to this force? It's smooth, so there is no friction. It rests on a horizontal guide, so the normal force is perpendicular, and thus purely vertical. Nothing else is attached to the roller, so no other forces are applied. The bar could apply a horizontal force to the roller, but that is internal to the system.
4) Nothing else contacts the system, and we've accounted for all relevant electro-magnetic/gravitational forces, and we haven't found any external forces along the X direction.
5) Based on this analysis of applied forces, as interpreted from the figure, there can be no net horizontal acceleration for the entire system. Assume that the acceleration of the COM is the acceleration of the entire system.

1) Yes, we should consider both OX and OY since we have a pin joint. You must do so whenever your system is constrained against a pin joint (but not if the pin is internal to your system!).
2) Regardless of the shape of an object, when gravity is the only force on the system, its center of mass will have an acceleration in Y only. The object is on a smooth surface, but gravity is not the only force on our system. Because we are using Newton-Euler equations and making our systems small, the cart exerts horizontal force on the block, and vice versa, so each is allowed to accelerate along X. If you take the net system of the block and cart together, the entire center of mass doesn't shift left or right.
3) In response to the follow up question, having as many small FBD's as possible with N-E problems does help.

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: Can someone explain the proof for why Wn^2=k/m?
Can you cancel out the cosine terms using the wavelength equation?

Yes. For the cosines in the EOM, you have (omega*t), but for the given cosine equation, you have (2*pi*z/L). Knowing that omega = (2pi/wavelength) and z = (velocity*time), you can simplify and figure out that they all cancel out.

If you start with Newton's Law: F= mx(doubledot) and have that equal a spring force kx, then the equation becomes mx(doubledot) = kx
which is the same as: mx(doubledot) - kx = 0
By solving this differential equation, the characteristic equation gives lambda1,lambda 2 = +/- sqrt(-4mk)/2m which simplifies to lambda, lambda 2 = +/- sqrt(k/m)i
This becomes an equation of the form Acos(wt)+B(sinwt) where w = sqrt(k/m)
The natural frequency is found assuming no damping and so therefore, even though this was a specific case, the coefficients K and M will always satisfy the natural frequency equation.
